                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Brenlo,
<br />

<br />
While I admit that I have no knowledge of the way that SoE has setup software development, I am familiar with the processes of developing software for hard real-time embedded systems.  As an embedded software engineer, I concern myself with how robust I can make my software so that in the event of a hardware failure, my software can recover.  We verify our software works as we intended by testing the software throughout its release cycle.  We setup the software testing in three tiers: the software testing, the lab environment testing, and then the actual final product testing.  The software developers provide tests and do an initial checkout on their desktops which simulates the hardware.  The lab environment uses the hardware and then the software is tested again on the hardware.  Finally, the software is verified within the actual hardware system.  At the end of our development cycle, we will have spent approximately 60 to 70 percent of our time testing the software, and only 20 percent of it is in development.
<br />

<br />
From my perspective I am the customer, and I have been a paying customer since March of 2000.  In that time, I have seen a vast change in the way that the game is played and the way that players interact with the game.  What I have noticed in particular, however, is that expansions seem to be released before the bugs are worked out.  These bugs are typically not something that causes the system to crash; instead, these are bugs that are entirely situational and result in allowing players to progress faster than desired or causes content to become trivial.  I think SoE officially calls these “exploits”.  From both perspectives of a player and a developer, these bugs are highly undesirable and take away from the “fun” of the game.  However, I believe these bugs can be addressed prior to releasing of an expansion through better testing and providing a way for a larger base of players to test out new content.
<br />

<br />
In my three tier explanation above, I would see the test server as the final checkout environment before releasing to the customer (“live” server).  I believe the test server provides great feedback because the customer can be involved within the testing of the latest software release (whether that is a patch or a completely new expansion).  Unfortunately, for a vast majority of people, there is little incentive for a player to go out and level up two characters.  Consequently, the players that have the greatest impact within the game and could provide the best feedback, are probably not on the test server.  And when a change is made quickly to band-aid an exploit, then those players feel as though they are slapped in the face.... It takes years to build up a customer's trust, but only seconds to lose one.
<br />

<br />
My proposal may be difficult to implement, but here is the thought:  Provide incentive by allowing a person to create a mirror of a particular character within their normal server.  The mirror character has an exact duplicate of all the gear, level, experience, flagging, etc.  However, no experience or items gained within the test server is reflected back on the normal server.  What this does is allow you to play one character “for real” within your normal server, but still have the ability to test out a change on the test server.  In addition, provide a means to “reset” the mirror by causing it to update with whatever the latest is for the character on the normal server.  This is as much of a benefit for SoE when they need feedback as it is for the player base who only has a limited amount of time to play.  In addition, it lets people who normally group together play on a test server and provide feedback... with a character they normally would play, and therefore you would get a much better sample of problems and issues with a particular expansion.
<br />

<br />
Thanks for taking the time to read this.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
